Dollar Cost Averaging and Value-Averaging Investement Strategies Comparison

Introduction

This project examines and compares two popular investment strategies: Dollar Cost Averaging (DCA) and Value Averaging (VA). We aim to identify which strategy may potentially yield better financial results using historical ETF data. We will conduct this analysis using several metrics such as total returns, volatility, and the Sharpe ratio.

Investment Strategies

Benchmark investment strategy

The benchmark strategy involves a one-time lump sum investment. This provides a baseline for comparing the other more dynamic investment strategies. The initial investment is set at $125,000. The code iterates over each month, updating the portfolio value based on the monthly return. Since no new units are purchased, units_bought_this_month and actual_investment remain zero throughout the simulation.

# Define the benchmark strategy function
benchmark_investment_strategy <- function(initial_investment, data) {
  
  # Initialize variables for portfolio value and results dataframe
  investment_portfolio <- initial_investment
  results <- data.frame(Month = integer(), Strategy = character(), Portfolio = numeric(), Returns = numeric())
  savings <- 0
  total_invested <- 125000
  total_units <- 125000/monthly_prices_df$prices[1]
  current_pru <- ifelse(total_units > 0, total_invested / total_units, 0)
  monthly_investment <- 0
  units_bought_this_month <- 0
  
  for (month in 2:nrow(data)) {
    
    # Calculate new portfolio value based on the monthly return
    investment_return <- data$returns[month]
    investment_portfolio <- investment_portfolio * (1 + investment_return)
    
    # Append the results for the current month to the results dataframe
    results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Month = month-1, Strategy = "Benchmark Investment", Total_units = total_units, Total_invested = total_invested, Units_to_buy = units_bought_this_month, Actual_investment = monthly_investment, Savings = savings, Portfolio_assets = investment_portfolio, Portfolio_Total = investment_portfolio + savings, PRU = current_pru, Returns = investment_return
 ))
  }

  return(results)
}

# Run the benchmark strategy
initial_investment <- 125000  # Initial investment amount
benchmark_results <- benchmark_investment_strategy(initial_investment, monthly_returns_df)
benchmark_results

The Benchmark Investment dataframe shows a constant number of total units and total invested amount because, in this strategy, all investment is made upfront, and no additional units are purchased over time. With this strategy we result with a portfolio total value of 300410.3$.

Dollar-Cost Averaging Strategy

Dollar-Cost Averaging is an investment strategy where a fixed amount is invested at regular intervals. The code snippet iterates through each month, calculates the number of units that can be bought with the monthly investment, and updates the portfolio value accordingly. This method can mitigate the impact of market volatility.

# Define the DCA function
dollar_cost_averaging <- function(initial_savings, monthly_savings, data) {
  savings <- initial_savings
  investment_portfolio <- 0
  total_invested <- 0
  total_units <- 0
  max_portfolio_value <- 0
  results <- data.frame(Month = integer(), Strategy = character(), Savings = numeric(), Portfolio = numeric(), PRU = numeric(), Drawdown = numeric())
  
  for (month in 1:(nrow(data) - 1)) {
    
    # Calculate the number of units to buy at current month's price
    monthly_investment <- savings
    units_to_buy <- floor(monthly_investment / monthly_prices_df$prices[month])
    actual_investment <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month]
    savings <- savings + monthly_savings - actual_investment 
    previous_portfolio_value <- investment_portfolio
    
    # Update the portfolio value including the investment gains
    investment_gains <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month] * (1 + data$returns[month+1])
    investment_portfolio <- investment_portfolio + investment_gains
    adjusted_portfolio_value <- previous_portfolio_value + actual_investment
    adjusted_return <- (investment_portfolio - adjusted_portfolio_value) / adjusted_portfolio_value
    total_invested <- total_invested + actual_investment
    total_units <- total_units + units_to_buy
    current_pru <- ifelse(total_units > 0, total_invested / total_units, 0)
    max_portfolio_value <- max(max_portfolio_value, investment_portfolio)
    current_drawdown <- (investment_portfolio - max_portfolio_value) / max_portfolio_value
    
    # Store the result for each month in the dataframe
    results <- rbind(results, data.frame(Month = month, Strategy = "Dollar-Cost Averaging", Total_units = total_units, Total_invested = total_invested, Units_to_buy = units_to_buy, Actual_investment = actual_investment, Savings = savings, Portfolio_assets = investment_portfolio, Portfolio_Total = investment_portfolio + savings, PRU = current_pru, Returns = adjusted_return))
  }
  
  return(results)
}

# Execute the DCA strategy
simulation_results_dca <- dollar_cost_averaging(1041.67, 1041.67, monthly_returns_df)
simulation_results_dca

The Dollar-Cost Averaging dataframe shows a gradual increase in total units and total invested amount. This aligns with the DCA strategy where a fixed amount is invested regularly, resulting in the purchase of more units over time. Value-Averaging Strategy

The Value-Averaging strategy adjusts the investment amount based on actual performance versus a target growth trajectory. This potentially results in buying more units when prices are low and fewer when prices are high. The code provided takes into account market conditions to adjust the investment dynamically.

# Define functions to adjust investment based on market conditions
calculate_investment_dynamic <- function(savings, market_condition) {
  investment_multiplier <- switch(market_condition,
                                  "bull" = 0.6,
                                  "neutral" = 1,
                                  "bear" = 1.4)
  investment <- min(1000 * investment_multiplier, savings - 400)
  return(investment)
}

# Define the dynamic allocation function for VA strategy
dynamic_allocation <- function(initial_savings, monthly_savings, data) {
  savings <- initial_savings
  investment_portfolio <- 0
  total_invested <- 0
  total_units <- 0
  max_portfolio_value <- 0
  monthly_investment <- 0
  investment_gains <- 0
  units_to_buy <- 0
  actual_investment <- 0
  results <- data.frame(Month = integer(), Strategy = character(), Monthly_investment = numeric(), Savings = numeric(), Portfolio = numeric(), PRU = numeric(), Drawdown = numeric())
  
  for (month in 1:(nrow(data) - 1)) {
    
    # Dynamic investment calculation based on market conditions
    returns <- data$returns[month]
    market_condition <- ifelse(data$returns[month] < -0.02, "bear",
                               ifelse(data$returns[month] > 0.02, "bull", "neutral"))
    monthly_investment <- calculate_investment_dynamic(savings, market_condition)
    units_to_buy <- floor(monthly_investment / monthly_prices_df$prices[month])
    actual_investment <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month]
    savings <- savings + monthly_savings - actual_investment
    previous_portfolio_value <- investment_portfolio
    investment_gains <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month] * (1+data$returns[month+1])
    investment_portfolio <- investment_portfolio + investment_gains
    adjusted_portfolio_value <- previous_portfolio_value + actual_investment
    adjusted_return <- (investment_portfolio - adjusted_portfolio_value) / adjusted_portfolio_value
    total_invested <- total_invested + actual_investment
    total_units <- total_units + units_to_buy
    current_pru <- ifelse(total_units > 0, total_invested / total_units, 0)
    max_portfolio_value <- max(max_portfolio_value, investment_portfolio)
    current_drawdown <- (investment_portfolio - max_portfolio_value) / max_portfolio_value
    
    # Update portfolio and results after buying new units
    results <- rbind(
      results,
      data.frame(
        Month = month,
        Strategy = "Dynamic Allocation",
        Total_units = total_units,
        Total_invested = total_invested,
        Units_to_buy = units_to_buy,
        Actual_investment = actual_investment,
        Savings = savings,
        Portfolio_assets = investment_portfolio,
        Portfolio_Total = investment_portfolio + savings,
        PRU = current_pru,
        Returns = adjusted_return
      )
    )
  }
  
  return(results)
}

# Execute the VA strategy
simulation_results_dynamic <- dynamic_allocation(5000, 1000, monthly_returns_df)
simulation_results_dynamic

The Dynamic Allocation dataframe illustrates a variable pattern in the Units_to_buy column, indicative of the VA strategys adjustment to market conditions. The Savings column fluctuates, which suggests that not all available funds are used in some months, likely due to market prices being higher. With this strategy we result with a portfolio total value of 126056.65$.

Interpretation

We can actually see a difference between the final total values of our 3 strategies. The benchmark strategy finishes well above, followed very closely by the DCA and the VA. This is completely normal because the exposure during the benchmark strategy is much longer and more important. In addition, the VA strategy is not very optimized and it does not completely tracking the returns of the underlying.

Performance Metrics

The performance metrics offers a detailed comparison of each strategys average return, geometric return, volatility, Sharpe Ratio, Value at Risk, and Maximum Drawdown across different ETFs. These metrics can help to evaluate the trade-offs between return and risk associated with each investment strategy.

Definition of functions

#Max drawdown function
calculate_max_drawdown <- function(returns, months) {
  # Assuming months start from a particular point in time ; April 2014
  start_date <- as.Date("2014-04-30")  # Change this base date as needed
  dates <- seq.Date(from = start_date, by = "month", length.out = length(months))

  # Create the xts object
  returns_xts <- xts(returns, order.by = dates)

  # Calculate Maximum Drawdown
  max_dd <- maxDrawdown(returns_xts)
  return(max_dd)
}


calculate_metrics <- function(data) {
  # Ensure data is cleaned of NAs specifically in 'Returns' and 'Month'
  data <- na.omit(data[, c("Returns", "Month")])

  returns <- as.numeric(data$Returns)
  months <- data$Month  # This is assuming 'Month' is correctly ordered and represents your time series

  average_return <- mean(returns)
  geometric_return <- exp(mean(log(1 + returns))) - 1
  volatility <- sd(returns)
  sharpe_ratio <- ifelse(volatility > 0, average_return / volatility, NA)
  var <- as.numeric(quantile(returns, 0.05, na.rm = TRUE) * -1)
  max_drawdown <- as.numeric(calculate_max_drawdown(returns, months))  # Pass months instead of dates

  return(list(
    average_return = average_return,
    geometric_return = geometric_return,
    volatility = volatility,
    sharpe_ratio = sharpe_ratio,
    var = var,
    max_drawdown = max_drawdown
  ))
}

New version of the Value Averaging strategy,

This model allows an allocation more proportional to the last months performance and can be optimized by maximizing its sharpe ratio.

Definition of the functions

calculate_investment_dynamic_updated <- function(savings, returns, value_averaging_weight) {
  
  # Dfinir le montant de base  investir
  base_investment <- 1000
  
  # Adjust the multiplier according to the return from the last period
  investment_multiplier <- 1 + (as.numeric(returns)*value_averaging_weight)

  # Calculate the investment amount, without exceeding what savings allow after a minimum safety reserve
  investment <- min(base_investment * investment_multiplier, savings - 400)

  # Make sure the investment is not negative  
  investment <- max(investment, 0)

  return(investment)
}

# Define the new dynamic allocation function for VA strategy
dynamic_allocation_updated <- function(initial_savings, monthly_savings, data, value_averaging_weight) {
  savings <- initial_savings
  investment_portfolio <- 0
  total_invested <- 0
  total_units <- 0
  max_portfolio_value <- 0
  monthly_investment <- 0
  investment_gains <- 0
  units_to_buy <- 0
  actual_investment <- 0
  results <- data.frame(Month = integer(), Strategy = character(), Monthly_investment = numeric(), Savings = numeric(), Portfolio = numeric(), PRU = numeric(), Drawdown = numeric())
  
  for (month in 1:(nrow(data) - 1)) {
    returns <- data$returns[month]
    monthly_investment <- calculate_investment_dynamic_updated(savings, returns, value_averaging_weight)
    units_to_buy <- floor(monthly_investment / monthly_prices_df$prices[month]) 
    actual_investment <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month]
    savings <- savings + monthly_savings - actual_investment
    previous_portfolio_value <- investment_portfolio
    investment_gains <- units_to_buy * monthly_prices_df$prices[month] * (1+data$returns[month+1])
    investment_portfolio <- investment_portfolio + investment_gains
    adjusted_portfolio_value <- previous_portfolio_value + actual_investment
    adjusted_return <- (investment_portfolio - adjusted_portfolio_value) / adjusted_portfolio_value
    total_invested <- total_invested + actual_investment
    total_units <- total_units + units_to_buy
    current_pru <- ifelse(total_units > 0, total_invested / total_units, 0)
    max_portfolio_value <- max(max_portfolio_value, investment_portfolio)
    current_drawdown <- (investment_portfolio - max_portfolio_value) / max_portfolio_value
    
    # Update portfolio and results after buying new units
    results <- rbind(
      results,
      data.frame(
        Month = month,
        Strategy = "Dynamic Allocation Updated",
        Total_units = total_units,
        Total_invested = total_invested,
        Units_to_buy = units_to_buy,
        Actual_investment = actual_investment,
        Savings = savings,
        Portfolio_assets = investment_portfolio,
        Portfolio_Total = investment_portfolio + savings,
        PRU = current_pru,
        Returns = adjusted_return
      )
    )
  }
  
  return(results)
}

Sharpe ratio optimization (Value-Averaging strategy)

The code tries to find the optimal weight that maximizes the Sharpe Ratio for the Value-Averaging strategy. A sequence of weights is tested, and the Sharpe Ratio is calculated for the portfolios returns resulting from each weight. The weight yielding the highest Sharpe Ratio is selected.

Definition of the sharpe ratio function

calculate_sharpe_ratio <- function(returns) {
  # Clean NA values from returns first
  returns <- na.omit(returns)
  
  # Check if returns has enough data
  if (length(returns) < 2 || var(returns) == 0) {
    return(NA)  # Return NA if not enough data or no variation
  }
  
  # Compute average return and standard deviation
  average_return <- mean(returns, na.rm = TRUE)
  sd_return <- sd(returns, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  # Prevent division by zero
  if (sd_return == 0) {
    return(NA)
  }
  
  # Calculate Sharpe Ratio
  sharpe_ratio <- average_return / sd_return
  return(sharpe_ratio)
}

Identifying the optimal weight to maximize your sharpe ratio

test_weights <- seq(0, 500, by = 1)  # Test weights from 0 to 500 with a step of 1
sharpe_ratios <- numeric(length(test_weights))
names(sharpe_ratios) <- as.character(test_weights)

for (weight in test_weights) {
  dynamic_results <- dynamic_allocation_updated(5000, 1000, monthly_returns_df, weight)
  returns <- dynamic_results$Returns  
  sharpe_ratios[as.character(weight)] <- calculate_sharpe_ratio(returns)
}

# Identification du poids qui maximise le Sharpe Ratio
best_weight <- test_weights[which.max(sharpe_ratios)]
best_sharpe_ratio <- max(sharpe_ratios)

Application and storage of the different strategies on ETFs

# List to store results for each ETF
etf_results <- list()
results <- list()
optimize_value_averaging_weight <- function(etf_data) {
    best_sharpe <- -Inf
    best_weight <- NULL
    test_weights <- seq(0, 100, by = 1)

    for (weight in test_weights) {
        dynamic_results <- dynamic_allocation_updated(5000, 1000, etf_data, weight)
        returns <- dynamic_results$Returns  # Ensure this column is correct and exists
        returns <- na.omit(returns)  # Clean NA values before processing
        sharpe_ratio <- calculate_sharpe_ratio(returns)

        if (!is.na(sharpe_ratio) && sharpe_ratio > best_sharpe) {
            best_sharpe <- sharpe_ratio
            best_weight <- weight
        }
    }

    return(list(best_weight = best_weight, best_sharpe = best_sharpe))
}

                                  Average.Return = benchmark_metrics$average_return,
                                  Geometric.Return = benchmark_metrics$geometric_return,
                                  Volatility = benchmark_metrics$volatility,
                                  Sharpe.Ratio = benchmark_metrics$sharpe_ratio,
                                  Value.at.Risk = benchmark_metrics$var,
                                  Maximum.Drawdown = benchmark_metrics$max_drawdown))
  
  # Calculate metrics for DCA strategy
  dca_metrics <- calculate_metrics(dca_results)
  all_metrics_df <- rbind(all_metrics_df, 
                         data.frame(ETF = etf, 
                                  Strategy = "DCA",
                                  Average.Return = dca_metrics$average_return,
                                  Geometric.Return = dca_metrics$geometric_return,
                                  Volatility = dca_metrics$volatility,
                                  Sharpe.Ratio = dca_metrics$sharpe_ratio,
                                  Value.at.Risk = dca_metrics$var,
                                  Maximum.Drawdown = dca_metrics$max_drawdown))
  
  # Calculate metrics for dynamic strategy
  dynamic_metrics <- calculate_metrics(dynamic_results)
  all_metrics_df <- rbind(all_metrics_df, 
                         data.frame(ETF = etf, 
                                  Strategy = "Dynamic",
                                  Average.Return = dynamic_metrics$average_return,
                                  Geometric.Return = dynamic_metrics$geometric_return,
                                  Volatility = dynamic_metrics$volatility,
                                  Sharpe.Ratio = dynamic_metrics$sharpe_ratio,
                                  Value.at.Risk = dynamic_metrics$var,
                                  Maximum.Drawdown = dynamic_metrics$max_drawdown))
}

# Calculate metric averages for all ETFs
average_metrics_df <- all_metrics_df %>%
  group_by(Strategy) %>%
  summarise(
    Average.Return = mean(Average.Return, na.rm = TRUE),
    Geometric.Return = mean(Geometric.Return, na.rm = TRUE),
    Volatility = mean(Volatility, na.rm = TRUE),
    Sharpe.Ratio = mean(Sharpe.Ratio, na.rm = TRUE),
    Value.at.Risk = mean(Value.at.Risk, na.rm = TRUE),
    Maximum.Drawdown = mean(Maximum.Drawdown, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

average_metrics_df_formatted <- average_metrics_df %>%

min_sharpe_avg <- which.min(average_metrics_df$Sharpe.Ratio)

Conclusion

We saw that investment strategies can vary widely in effectiveness depending on the market conditions represented by different ETFs.

The dynamic allocation strategy appears to adapt more successfully to market changes, as indicated by its performance metrics, especially in terms of the Sharpe Ratio, which is often higher than those of the other strategies. Dollar-Cost Averaging shows a consistent performance across various ETFs, indicating that it can be a less risky strategy albeit sometimes with lower returns.

The benchmark strategy, which represents a lump-sum investment, can sometimes lead to higher average returns but also comes with higher volatility and drawdowns, highlighting the trade-off between risk and return.

In terms of investment, while the Dynamic Allocation strategy seems to provide a good balance between risk and return, individual investors must consider their risk tolerance, investment horizon, and the specific market conditions of the ETFs they are interested in before choosing a strategy.

The dynamic allocation strategy is particularly suitable for someone with a steady income who can save monthly, rather than investing a large sum all at once. Its more attuned to the typical financial situation of a salaried employee, allowing for regular investments that align with monthly cash flow, mitigating risk, and potentially maximizing returns through strategic adjustments based on market conditions. This approach can offer a practical and less daunting path to investment compared to a one-time, upfront benchmark investment strategy.

calculate_etf_metrics <- function(etf, years) {
  start_date <- as.Date(Sys.Date()) - years
  getSymbols(etf, src = "yahoo", from = start_date, to = Sys.Date(), auto.assign = TRUE)
  monthly_prices <- to.monthly(get(etf), indexAt = "lastof", OHLC = FALSE)
  monthly_returns <- na.omit(periodReturn(monthly_prices, period = 'monthly', type = 'log'))
  etf_data <- data.frame(date = index(monthly_returns), returns = as.numeric(coredata(monthly_returns)), prices = as.numeric(coredata(monthly_prices[,4])))
  
  if (nrow(etf_data) > 0) {
    optimization_results <- optimize_value_averaging_weight(etf_data)
    best_weight <- optimization_results$best_weight
    
    benchmark_results <- benchmark_investment_strategy(125000, etf_data)
    dca_results <- dollar_cost_averaging(1041.67, 1041.67, etf_data)
    dynamic_results <- dynamic_allocation_updated(5000, 1000, etf_data, best_weight)
    
    return(list(
      Benchmark = calculate_metrics(benchmark_results),
      DCA = calculate_metrics(dca_results),
      Dynamic = calculate_metrics(dynamic_results),
      BestWeight = best_weight,
      BestSharpe = optimization_results$best_sharpe
    ))
  } else {
    return(list())
  }
}

results_by_time_horizon <- lapply(time_horizons, function(years) {
  sapply(etfs, function(etf) calculate_etf_metrics(etf, years), simplify = FALSE)
})

# Creation of a dataframe to compare performance by ETF
performance_comparison <- data.frame(
  ETF = character(),
  Strategy = character(),
  Sharpe = numeric(),
  Return = numeric(),
  Risk = numeric()
)

for (etf in etfs) {
  if (!is.null(results[[etf]])) {
    for (strategy in c("Benchmark", "DCA", "Dynamic")) {
      if (!is.null(results[[etf]][[strategy]])) {
        performance_comparison <- rbind(performance_comparison, data.frame(
          ETF = etf,
          Strategy = strategy,
          Sharpe = results[[etf]][[strategy]]$sharpe_ratio,
          Return = results[[etf]][[strategy]]$average_return,
          Risk = results[[etf]][[strategy]]$volatility
        ))
      }
    }
  }
}

Implications for the Investment Strategy

These graphical analyses allow us to draw several important conclusions for the investment strategy:

  1. Market strategy selection:
  • For developed markets (URTH, SPY): prefer the Benchmark strategy
  • For emerging markets (EEM): consider the Dynamic strategy
  • Avoid the DCA for long-term investments in these markets2.

Risk considerations: - Dynamic and DCA strategies can be used to reduce risk, but at the cost of potentially lower returns - Benchmark strategy, although riskier, offers the best risk-adjusted performance on developed markets3.

Diversification: - Performance differences between ETFs and strategies underline the importance of geographic diversification - Combining different strategies across markets could optimize the portfolios overall risk-return profile

These results suggest that a hybrid approach, adapting the strategy to the target market, could be more effective than a uniform application of a single investment strategy.
